        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical mixing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "You do not need to calculate ratios precisely. The working rule for"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "browns-and-greens"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "browns and greens"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "is roughly equal volumes (not weights). A bucket of grass clippings with a bucket of torn cardboard produces a mix in the right range. If the heap smells of ammonia, add more browns. If nothing is happening and the heap looks dry and woody, add more greens and water."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why particle size matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The C:N ratio is about chemistry; particle size is about surface area. A sheet of cardboard at 400:1 decomposes slowly: it is carbon-rich and its surface area per gram is tiny compared to shredded cardboard. Shredding, chopping, or mowing over leaves before composting cuts breakdown time by 50-75% regardless of C:N ratio, because it increases the surface available to microbial attack."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
